{{Otheruses|石人山古墳 in Hirokawa, Fukuoka|the kofun in Miyama, Fukuoka|Sekijinzan Kofun}} {{Infobox ancient site|type = [[Zenpokoenfun]]| name=石人山古墳| image =[[File:Sekijinsan kofun.jpg|240px]] |part_of={{ill|Yame Kofun Cluster|ja|八女古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yame Kofun Cluster|qq=}}| location={{ill|Hirokawa, Fukuoka|ja|広川町 (福岡県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirokawa, Fukuoka|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Prefecture|qq=}}| coordinates={{coord|33|14|14.5|N|130|31|03.4|E|region:JP-40|display=inline,title}}| Shape={{ill|Zenpokoenfun|ja|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|qq=}}| area=Total length 107 m| built=Early to mid-5th century| Burial Facility={{ill|Yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}| Interred Persons=(Presumed) Grandfather of {{ill|Tsunokimi Iwai|ja|筑紫君磐井|3=磐井 (古代豪族)|1=Tsukushi no Iwai|2=ja|1=Tsukushi no Iwai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsunokimi Iwai|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukushi no Iwai|qq=}}| Excavated Artifacts=Stone figures, haniwa| Historic Site Designation=Designated as a [[National Historic Site of Japan]] in {{ill|Shōwa 13|ja|昭和13rd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa 13|qq=}} (1938)| Special Notes={{ill|Decorated kofun|ja|装飾古墳|1=Decorated kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Decorated kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Decorated kofun|qq=}}}}
'''Sekijinzan Kofun''' (石人山古墳) is a {{ill|Zenpokoenfun|ja|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|qq=}} located in {{ill|Hirokawa, Fukuoka|ja|広川町 (福岡県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirokawa, Fukuoka|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Prefecture|qq=}}. It is part of the {{ill|Yame Kofun Cluster|ja|八女古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yame Kofun Cluster|qq=}} and has been Historic Site1 as a [[National Historic Site of Japan]].
The tomb is believed to be the burial site of the grandfather of {{ill|Tsunokimi Iwai|ja|筑紫君磐井|3=磐井 (古代豪族)|1=Tsukushi no Iwai|2=ja|1=Tsukushi no Iwai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsunokimi Iwai|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukushi no Iwai|qq=}}. It was previously associated with Tsunokimi Iwai himself.<ref name=iwato>{{cite book|title=岩戸山歴史資料館 展示図録|pages=14-16}}</ref>
== Overview == * Mound length: Approximately 107 meters<ref name=iwato /> * Front section width: Approximately 63 meters; height: Approximately 11 meters * Rear section diameter: Approximately 53 meters; height: Approximately 12 meters
The tumulus consists of two tiers in the front section and three tiers in the rear. A {{ill|Tsukuridashi|ja|造出|1=Platform-style projection|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuridashi|13=User:Immanuelle/Platform-style projection|qq=}} structure remains in the northern constriction area. The mound originally had surrounding moats and embankments, remnants of which can still be observed on the west side of the front section and the east side of the rear section.
Based on its type and the dating of Sue pottery burial goods, the tumulus is believed to have been constructed in the early to mid-5th century. It is thought to predate {{ill|Iwatozan Kofun|ja|岩戸山古墳|1=Iwato-yama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwatozan Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwato-yama Kofun|qq=}}, the burial site of Tsunokimi Iwai, by several generations, potentially making it the tomb of Iwai’s grandfather.<ref name=iwato />
The kofun was Historic Site1 as a [[National Historic Site of Japan]] on August 8, 1938. On March 24, 1978, additional Historic Sites and integrations expanded its status under the name {{ill|Yame Kofun Cluster|ja|八女古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yame Kofun Cluster|qq=}}.<ref>{{cite book|title=図説日本の史跡3 原始3|publisher=同朋舎出版|year=1991|pages=206}}</ref><ref>The pre-existing Historic Sites for {{ill|Iwatozan Kofun|ja|岩戸山古墳|1=Iwato-yama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwatozan Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwato-yama Kofun|qq=}}, {{ill|Noriba Kofun|ja|乗場古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noriba Kofun|qq=}}, Sekijinzan Kofun, {{ill|Zenzōzuka Kofun|ja|善蔵塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenzōzuka Kofun|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kōkayadani Kofun|ja|弘化谷古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōkayadani Kofun|qq=}} were integrated, and three additional kofun (Maruyamazuka Kofun, Maruyama Kofun, Chausuzuka Kofun) were included under the unified Historic Site.</ref>
=== burial Chamber === [[File:石人山古墳家型石棺.JPG|thumb|House-shaped sarcophagus]] At the center of the rear section is an ancient {{ill|Yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoana-shiki sekishitsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} constructed with flat stones of green chlorite schist. Inside, a horizontal, assembled {{ill|house-shaped sarcophagus|ja|家形石棺|1=House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/house-shaped sarcophagus|13=User:Immanuelle/House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=}} is placed. The lid features a {{ill|kirizuma|ja|寄棟造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kirizuma|qq=}} roof design, with a base length of 2.8 meters and a suspension groove on the gable for a stone sword. The body comprises four slabs, with area of 2.3 meters in length and 1.4 meters in height.
The lid is adorned with relief carvings of arc patterns and concentric circles, painted in cinnabar, making it a significant early example of decorated kofun.<ref name=iwato /> Although the stone chamber was opened during the Edo period and its ceiling is now missing,<ref>{{cite book|title=日本古墳大辞典|page=313}}</ref> it is protected by a facility that allows visitors to view it.
=== Stone Figure === [[File:石人山古墳石人.JPG|thumb|upright|Stone figure]] In front of the stone chamber, a {{ill|stone human figure|ja|石人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone human figure|qq=}}, Historic Site1 as an Important designation1 of Japan, is displayed in the {{ill|Sekijin Shrine|ja|石人社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekijin Shrine|qq=}}. This armed figure, which gave the kofun its name, stands with its back to the chamber. The figure, along with a similar one from {{ill|Sekijinsan Kofun|lt=Sekijinsan Kofun|lt=Ishigamiyama Kofun|ja|石神山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishigamiyama Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Miyama, Fukuoka|ja|みやま市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyama, Fukuoka|qq=}}, is among the oldest of its kind in the Southern Chikugo region.<ref name=iwato />
Carved from Aso welded tuff, the figure measures approximately 1.8 meters in height. It wears a triangular plate cuirass and {{ill|kusazuri|ja|草摺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kusazuri|qq=}}, and a groove on its left side indicates where a stone sword was once attached.<ref name=iwato />
The figure's face is now eroded, and its upper body patterns are unclear. Historical sketches from the Edo period depict its original appearance, showing eyes, a nose, and a mouth. It is believed that the figure became worn over time due to a folk practice of touching or striking it to cure physical ailments.<ref>[http://www.city.chikugo.lg.jp/kankou/_1070/_6135/_1088.html 石人山古墳の武装石人 - 筑後市]</ref>
